{
  "text": "A closer approximation of the Walrasian ideal of anonymous exchange (recall Buchanan at the fruit stand) renders the evolution of socially useful norms unlikely. We will give two examples, the first being perhaps the archetype of a coordination failure: the prisoners' dilemma. The likelihood that a given prisoners' dilemma game played iteratively will support an equilibrium strategy leading to mutually beneficial cooperation rather than mutually costly defection is known to depend on the likelihood that each round of the game will be repeated [CITATION_1] . The reason is that where repetition is likely, the implicit threat of retaliation against defection is effective, thus encouraging agents to chance cooperation. When markets approximate the anonymity of the Walrasian model, however, the likelihood of such repeated interactions is small. Thus unconditional defection becomes the dominant strategy, leading to a lower payoff for all players.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "155083865"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "155083865": {
      "title": "The Evolution of Cooperation",
      "abstract": "Cooperation in organisms, whether bacteria or primates, has been a difficulty for evolutionary theory since Darwin. On the assumption that interactions between pairs of individuals occur on a probabilistic basis, a model is developed based on the concept of an evolutionarily stable strategy in the context of the Prisoner's Dilemma game. Deductions from the model, and the results of a computer tournament show how cooperation based on reciprocity can get started in an asocial world, can thrive while interacting with a wide range of other strategies, and can resist invasion once fully established. Potential applications include specific aspects of territoriality, mating, and disease."
    }
  }
}